Sotheby=E2=80=99s must have been pleased by the crowds that turned up on Su=
nday for the auction preview of artworks belonging to the late Palm Beach g=
rande dame Sydell Miller, expected to make $200 million. Yes, there was a b=
ig eye-catching Monet to chase, not to mention a Matisse and three Lalanne =
tables. But the self-made beauty mogul=E2=80=99s taste was idiosyncratic=E2=
=80=94or, at least, not on theme with what most collectors are pursuing the=
se days.

Nevertheless, the crowds showed up, and returned the next night, as the ind=
ustry assembled in a way we haven=E2=80=99t seen for a few seasons. Impress=
ionist and modern evening sales have lost their verve in the art market: Th=
ese days, most of the action takes place across the phone banks while the w=
ebcast cameras pivot back and forth between whispering specialists. But on =
Monday
night at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the crowd of dealers and art advisors arrived e=
arly to mingle and schmooze in the lobby. Some were ready to bid, others we=
re there just to catch the vibe. A few, one private dealer suggested, may h=
ave been secretly hoping for the drama of a tough night, similar to the hea=
rt-in-throat Gerald Fineberg sale of contemporary art at Christie=E2=80=99s=
 a year and a half ago.

Whatever their motivation, the onlookers stayed late enough to witness soli=
d demand, proving that the art market has not been squelched by a lack of d=
ry powder. Instead, the problem has been a lack of material exciting enough=
 to tempt buyers. And yet, the Miller sale, and some isolated works from th=
e various-owners sales, demonstrated that buyers are willing to chase speci=
fic lots that have been priced to sell and, in some cases, validated by thi=
rd-party guarantors.

