White Gloves

All 25 Miller lots sold=E2=80=94a feat known as a =E2=80=9Cwhite glove sale=
=E2=80=9D in the trade. When these sales happen, they look easy, belying th=
e fact that they require a lot of work behind the scenes. The Miller family=
 had help from a large team of advisors, including former Sotheby=E2=80=99s=
 specialist David Norman. Miller had been a client of Norman=E2=80=99s 25 y=
ears ago, and now Norman was helping to price the works in a way that would=
 draw bidders=E2=80=94the family declined to take a guarantee=E2=80=94and s=
electively field irrevocable bids. In the end, the Miller heirs took seven =
irrevocable bids=E2=80=94as Sotheby=E2=80=99s calls them, or =E2=80=9Cthird=
-party guarantees=E2=80=9D to the rest of the art world.

That was a smart move. In the end, four of the top six prices in the Miller=
 sale came with irrevocable bids. Over the weekend, yet another art advisor=
 mentioned to me that their
clients have begun to view the third-party guarantees as a vote of confiden=
ce in a work and an encouragement to bid. That view seemed to have borne ou=
t on the big Monet, Kandinsky, Yves Klein, and Henry Moore works that the M=
iller family sold. Those seven irrevocable bids accounted for over half of =
the sale=E2=80=99s total value.

In the case of the Monet waterlilies ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auct=
