shed-out Rothko work on paper ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/202=
4/a-legacy-of-beauty-the-collection-of-sydell-miller-evening-auction/untitl=
ed?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&u=
tm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail=
_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that had b=
een estimated at $2 million and sold for $5.1 million. The ocher and pale y=
ellow work had a long and distinguished provenance, including the fashion d=
esigner Hubert de Givenchy, but has yet to be included in Rothko=E2=80=99s =
catalogue raisonn=C3=A9 for works on paper. You can see how the irrevocable=
 bid might have been helpful here, and it was. (There were two minor Rothko=
s in the various-owners sale that followed, but neither came close to reach=
ing the estimate.)

Lalannes Lead the Way

One place where Miller=E2=80=99s taste matches the current market momentum =
is in her love of Les Lalannes. The evening sale included three tables, one=
 by Fran=C3=A7ois-Xavier Lalanne, the surrealist sculptor/furniture designe=
r now dominating the auction market, and two by his wife, Claude. The first=
 to sell ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/a-legacy-of-beauty-=
the-collection-of-sydell-miller-evening-auction/troupeau-delephants-dans-le=
s-arbres-table?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F=
19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
) was an example of the =E2=80=9Ctroop of elephants
among trees=E2=80=9D table. Miller had owned two of these. One was sold thr=
ee years ago for $6.6 million. Initially, Monday night=E2=80=99s bidding wa=
s quite slow, and it seemed the table would get knocked down for a price be=
low the previous sale.

But slow bidding isn=E2=80=99t necessarily feckless bidding, and the price =
reached an even $10 million=E2=80=94$6 million above the estimate. The fina=
l selling price of $11.6 million wasn=E2=80=99t double the previous price b=
ut still close enough to impress.

Miller had commissioned Claude Lalanne to make two tables with a waterlily =
theme to accompany her Monet. The first sold ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/=
buy/auction/2024/a-legacy-of-beauty-the-collection-of-sydell-miller-evening=
-auction/a-unique-nenuphars-console-table?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBER=
S+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) for $3.84 million above a $1.5 million estimat=
e. But the second table ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/a-le=
gacy-of-beauty-the-collection-of-sydell-miller-evening-auction/a-unique-nen=
uphars-console-table-2?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%2=
9&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da4=
2abd12a ) in the set went for only $2.16 million to a different buyer. To m=
ost of us, that result seems
nonsensical: How could two such similar works reach such different prices? =
That=E2=80=99s what we
mean by a connoisseur=E2=80=99s market: The buyers here have persnickety wa=
nts, and what may seem identical to the uninitiated can be glaringly differ=
ent to the connoisseur. Also, once the first table was sold and the buyer s=
howed they weren=E2=80=99t going to pursue the second table, there was one =
bidder fewer driving the price forward.

All of this isn=E2=80=99t to say the Miller sale was without miscalculation=
s. The large Dubuffet of mixed oil and acrylic paints was estimated at $2.5=
 million, which proved far too ambitious. The work was offered and failed t=
o sell when bidding reached $1.6 million. It passed. Just before the end of=
 the sale, auctioneer Oliver Barker brought the work back to the block. But=
 this time, he could only eke out bids up to $1.25 million=E2=80=94which wa=
s accepted. Barker is a superbly talented auctioneer=E2=80=94but even he ca=
n=E2=80=99t make up for a bidder=E2=80=99s disappointment and, perhaps, spi=
te. In the end, it cost the family around half a million to
secure the white glove bragging rights (or simply to not have to deal with =
selling the work privately). Of course, the $215.9 million in the bank from=
 the rest of the sale is likely consolation enough.

