Various Owners, Various Stories

Sydell Miller was not the only selling point at the auctions last night. Th=
e various-owners sale of modern material had several transactions that were=
 telling, each in its own way. Buyers may have money, but the overall marke=
t mood is still picky.

The run of female surrealists at the beginning of the sale showed solid res=
ults for Remedios Varo ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/moder=
n-evening-auction-2/los-caminos-tortuosos?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBER=
S+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Leonor Fini ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy=
/auction/2024/modern-evening-auction-2/les-stylites-les-stylists?locale=3De=
n&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3D=
Wall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_s=
ource=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), and Leonora Carrington=
=2E Another Carrington was sold at the end=20
( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/modern-evening-auction-2/tem=
ple-of-the-word?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2=
F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_m=
edium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a=
 ), also for a solid number. The most eye-catching of the works was the 6-f=
oot-tall sculpture ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/modern-ev=
ening-auction-2/la-grande-dame-the-cat-woman?locale=3Den&utm_campaign=3DWal=
l+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) by Carrington, La Grande Dame, which was bo=
ught by Eduardo Costantini, the Argentine collector, for $11.3 million.

The Tiffany Studios window was sold ( https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/aucti=
on/2024/modern-evening-auction-2/the-danner-memorial-window?locale=3Den&utm=
_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+=
Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) at a huge price of nearly $1=
1.4 million, with fees, above a $5 million estimate. That price doesn=E2=80=
=99t include the installation necessary to get the same effect Sotheby=E2=
=80=99s was able to create in the preview. (Though I=E2=80=99m sure the auc=
tion house
would be willing to throw in the recording of atmospheric morning soundscap=
es to the successful bidder.)

Paul Signac=E2=80=99s Antibes. La Pointe de Bacon, from 1917, which had bee=
n in the same family for 70 years, attracted a lot of bidding and sold for =
$9.95 million with fees over a $6 million estimate. Henri-Edmond Cross=E2=
=80=99s Eucalyptus et oliviers, from 1907, held by the Farkas family for mo=
re than 50 years, also did well, at $1.38 million with fees.

Franz Marc=E2=80=99s Das Lange Gelbe Pferd (The Long Yellow Horse), from 19=
13, failed to get bids to even half the $8 million estimate. It went unsold=
=2E An Ernst Ludwig Kirchner train scen=
e made a price below the estimate, but=
 a Max Beckmann sold well at $2.4 million with fees. That was over a $1.5 m=
illion estimate.

It was a rough night for Pablo Picasso. The titan of modern art has seen hi=
s auction sales dwindle this year. According
to ARTDAI=E2=80=99s numbers, $580 million in Picasso=E2=80=99s art was auct=
ioned in 2023. So far in 2024, that number is $191 million. Miller=E2=80=99=
s large painting from 1925 depicting a sculptress isn=E2=80=99t quite what =
current collectors are looking for. The bidding stopped far short of the $3=
0 million that Sotheby=E2=80=99s and the Miller family were hoping for. It =
sold for $24.8 million with fees. Considering that performance, the Neumann=
 family=E2=80=99s Buste de femme from 1949 did quite well by getting bids t=
o $8.5 million, just below the $9 million estimate. Another Picasso priced =
at $7 million was withdrawn despite, or maybe because, it was guaranteed by=
 Sotheby=E2=80=99s. A work on paper and a late painting were bought in. And=
 two other works that were backed by irrevocable bids sold at or just above=
 the estimate.

Henri Matisse had a mixed night, too. Miller=E2=80=99s 1942 portrait, Jeune=
 fille en robe rose, was estimated at $3 million, but saw strong bidding to=
 $8.3
million, or nearly three times the estimate. The final price was $9.73 mill=
ion. Later, in the various-owners sale, a Matisse odalisque from a Japanese=
 collection, and backed by a direct guarantee from Sotheby=E2=80=99s, was o=
ffered with a $12 million estimate. A similar image from around the same pe=
riod in the early 1920s sold for $14.3 million in 2018. But the appetite fo=
r this work was no longer there. It was =E2=80=9Cbought in,=E2=80=9D as the=
y say in the business, without a single bid.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

That=E2=80=99s my fairly exhaustive account of the evening. You can find me=
 in auction rooms around New York all week. Many of you were kind enough to=
 say hello last night at Sotheby=E2=80=99s. It=E2=80=99s really nice to mee=
t you all.

Speak to you Sunday,
M

