          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Sotheby=E2=80=99s m=
ust have been pleased by the crowds that turned up on Sunday for the auctio=
n preview of artworks belonging to the late Palm Beach grande dame <b>Sydel=
l Miller</b>,<b> </b>expected to make $200 million. Yes, there was a big ey=
e-catching <b>Monet</b> to chase, not to mention a <b>Matisse</b> and three=
 <b>Lalanne</b> tables. But the self-made beauty mogul=E2=80=99s taste was =
idiosyncratic=E2=80=94or, at least, not on theme with what most collectors =
are pursuing these days.<br/><br/>Nevertheless, the crowds showed up, and r=
eturned the next night, as the industry assembled in a way we haven=E2=80=
=99t seen for a few seasons. Impressionist and modern evening sales have lo=
st their verve in the art market: These days, most of the action takes plac=
e across the phone banks while the webcast cameras pivot back and forth bet=
ween whispering specialists. But on Monday
night at Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the crowd of dealers and art advisors arrived e=
arly to mingle and schmooze in the lobby. Some were ready to bid, others we=
re there just to catch the vibe. A few, one private dealer suggested, may h=
ave been secretly hoping for the drama of a tough night, similar to the hea=
rt-in-throat <b>Gerald Fineberg</b> sale of contemporary art at Christie=E2=
=80=99s a year and a half ago.<br/><br/>Whatever their motivation, the onlo=
okers stayed late enough to witness solid demand, proving that the art mark=
et has not been squelched by a lack of dry powder. Instead, the problem has=
 been a lack of material exciting enough to tempt buyers. And yet, the Mill=
er sale, and some isolated works from the various-owners sales, demonstrate=
d that buyers are willing to chase specific lots that have been priced to s=
ell and, in some cases, validated by third-party guarantors.  <br/></td>
         </tr>
