          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">All 25 Miller lots =
sold=E2=80=94a feat known as a =E2=80=9Cwhite glove sale=E2=80=9D in the tr=
ade. When these sales happen, they look easy, belying the fact that they re=
quire a lot of work behind the scenes. The Miller family had help from a la=
rge team of advisors, including former Sotheby=E2=80=99s specialist <b>Davi=
d Norman</b>. Miller had been a client of Norman=E2=80=99s 25 years ago, an=
d now Norman was helping to price the works in a way that would draw bidder=
s=E2=80=94the family declined to take a guarantee=E2=80=94and selectively f=
ield irrevocable bids. In the end, the Miller heirs took seven irrevocable =
bids=E2=80=94as Sotheby=E2=80=99s calls them, or =E2=80=9Cthird-party guara=
ntees=E2=80=9D to the rest of the art world. <br/><br/>That was a smart mov=
e. In the end, four of the top six prices in the Miller sale came with irre=
vocable bids. Over the weekend, yet another art advisor mentioned to me tha=
t their
clients have begun to view the third-party guarantees as a vote of confiden=
ce in a work and an encouragement to bid. That view seemed to have borne ou=
